Elizabeth Tucker Widow the Relict and Sole Executrix named in the said will to whom the Administration was committed of the Goods, Chattels and Credits of the said deceased being first sworn by Commission duly to Administer.

The death of Elizabeth Tucker, July 1736 [300] Will of Elizabeth Tucker TNA, PROB 11/678/209

In the name of God Amen. | Elizabeth Tucker of the Antient Town of Rye in the County of Sussex Widow being sick and weak in Body but of sound and disposing mind memory and understanding (God be praised for the same) do this twenty fifth day of February in the ninth year of the reign of Sovereign Lord George the second by the Grace of God King of Great Britain in France and Ireland defender of the faith etc. and in the year of our Lord 1735 make and ordain this my last Will and Testament in manner and form following (that is to say) in the first place I resign my soul to God my creator assuredly trusting through the meritts and mediation of my Lord and Saviour Jesus Christ to receive full pardon of all my sins and my Body I commit to the Earth to receive a devout private buriall at the discretion of my Executors hereafter named and as for my Wordly Estate I dispose thereof as follows. Item I give and bequeath unto my son Samuel Jeake the sume of one hundred and fifty pounds of lawfull money of Great Britain and if I shall happen to survive till after the five and twentieth day of March next (then and in such case and not otherwise) I give and bequeath unto my said son Samuel Jeake the further sume of fifty pounds of like lawful money making together two hundred pounds also I give and bequeath to the said Samuel Jeake one large silver Tankard with a Foot marked I" B, two silver porringers" one large the other small marked each S I, one double Rose Noble peice of Gold, the feather Bedd whereon he lyes with the Steadle covering and appurtenances thereunto belonging, the furniture of the best parlour (vizt) ten chairs the chimney glass and stoutes with the Furniture of the firehearth and all his late Father Jeakes Library of Books as contained in a Catalogue. Item I give and bequeath unto my daughter Barbara Jeake the summe of one thousand five hundred pounds of lawfull money of Great Britain (the summe of one hundred and eighty pounds upon a Mortgage made by John Tilden of Cranbrook in the County of Kent Timber broker to the said Barbara bearing date the two and twentieth day of June which was in the year of our Lord 1719 and all such moneys as were given or that she may claime a right to

*'A shallow bowl.
